WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.570
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to look at why infinite sets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:17.190
don't really exist. I'm going to start&nbsp;
to try to explain that, even though it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.190 --> 00:00:22.470
a very controversial position and most of my&nbsp;
fellow mathematicians will not agree with me.

00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:29.610
Let's first talk a little bit about regular&nbsp;
set theory, which is a useful addition to our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.610 --> 00:00:38.040
tool chest. A set is a collection of mathematical&nbsp;
objects, and it's agreed that all the objects in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:44.520
the set have to be distinct and the order in which&nbsp;
we present them is unimportant. So here's a set:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:53.100
{1, 3, 5, 7, 9}. It happens to be the set of all&nbsp;
odd numbers less than 10. It has five elements in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:57.630
it. These we can match; each one of the elements&nbsp;
with a 1, so we have a string of ones which we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.630 --> 00:01:05.610
usually call 5. We say the size of S is 5.&nbsp;
Here's another set, P, which consists of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:13.650
prime numbers less than 10. Its size is 4. There&nbsp;
are two fundamental things we can do with sets:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.650 --> 00:01:19.020
we can take their intersection, that is, create&nbsp;
a new set which consists of those elements which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:25.650
are common to both sets, or we can create the&nbsp;
union, which is the set of elements which are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.650 --> 00:01:35.850
either in one set or in another. So this kind&nbsp;
of set theory is useful and very practical.

00:01:35.850 --> 00:01:44.850
But in the 1870s, Georg Cantor, a German&nbsp;
mathematician, introduced a dramatic new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:54.960
suggestion. He said, why don't we consider also&nbsp;
infinite sets? This caused a lot of consternation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:02.280
it caused a lot of discussion and controversy,&nbsp;
and it ultimately became a very popular way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:08.130
thinking about a lot of mathematics, so much&nbsp;
so that it is now the orthodoxy. Let's have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.130 --> 00:02:16.410
a look at the simplest example of an infinite&nbsp;
set. Here is the set that's usually called N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:24.390
standing for natural numbers. It's a set whose&nbsp;
elements are all the natural numbers—all in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:31.650
quotes—1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8... you keep&nbsp;
going and keep going and keep going until&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.650 --> 00:02:39.180
the end of time and beyond. And all the natural&nbsp;
numbers are contained in those brackets. That,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:46.290
according to Cantor, was a new mathematical&nbsp;
object, which is now on a par with, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:53.490
the number 5 or the set S that we defined earlier.&nbsp;
We can manipulate that object, we can use it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:58.800
in other mathematical formulations, we can do&nbsp;
things with it just like we can with numbers.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:07.830
Well, this was historically very unprecedented.&nbsp;
For thousands of years previous to Cantor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:13.500
people had been very nervous and respectful&nbsp;
about the magnitude and the immensity of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:21.030
infinite sequences. So, to the ancient Greeks,&nbsp;
for example, the natural numbers were a sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:28.110
that progressed beyond our view. Looking further&nbsp;
and further in the sequence required more and more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.110 --> 00:03:36.690
powerful techniques, but nowhere can you enclose&nbsp;
all of those integers in a completed whole. That&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.690 --> 00:03:42.690
was the traditional point of view. But Cantor&nbsp;
said, no, no, we can. And not surprisingly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:48.690
he generated a lot of controversy. There were&nbsp;
many very prominent opponents of Cantor's theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:56.250
including Kronecker, Poincaré, Brouwer,&nbsp;
Weyl, and others. This list includes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.250 --> 00:04:04.740
some of the greatest mathematicians of the last&nbsp;
hundred years. It became clear also that Gauss,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:09.090
who lived before Cantor's time, had also&nbsp;
expressed an opinion on these matters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:14.650
and he was also opposed to the idea of&nbsp;
considering infinity as a completed whole.

00:04:14.650 --> 00:04:21.100
On top of these objections, Cantor also had&nbsp;
to deal with paradoxes. People started to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:26.170
discover paradoxes in the new theory that&nbsp;
Cantor had created. So there are famous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:34.240
paradoxes due to Burali-Forti, to Russell, and&nbsp;
indeed to Cantor himself. So by around 1900,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:39.070
the new theory was immersed in difficulties&nbsp;
and was being attacked on all sides,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:42.670
and at that time, it probably&nbsp;
looked like it was doomed.

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:51.850
Alright, now if we fast forward to 2024, we find a&nbsp;
remarkable change in circumstances. Now, infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.850 --> 00:05:01.420
sets are universally acknowledged as making sense.&nbsp;
Almost all modern mathematical objects are defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:06.910
in terms of infinite sets. So this object here,&nbsp;
which many of you will recognize as a circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:12.850
according to a pure mathematician, this is&nbsp;
actually an infinite set of points. You can't see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.850 --> 00:05:18.490
them all, but there is actually an infinite set&nbsp;
of points there. A square, that's also an infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.490 --> 00:05:25.450
set of points. So is even a lowly line segment.&nbsp;
A torus, or donut, is an infinite set of points.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:33.610
A function like f(x) = x^2 is defined in terms&nbsp;
of an infinite set of points. If a mathematician&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:39.280
looked at a tomato like this, probably they&nbsp;
would see an infinite amount of tomato points.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:46.600
How can this come about? How is it possible&nbsp;
that there was such a dramatic change? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:54.820
in my opinion, it's because of a distortion&nbsp;
of mathematical logic. Currently, we have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.820 --> 00:06:01.540
theory of so-called axiomatic set theory,&nbsp;
where mathematicians build philosophical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:06.970
castles in the sky and they proclaim that&nbsp;
these make sense because they say, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.970 --> 00:06:12.370
let's just assume that they do. We'll assume&nbsp;
that they do by stating certain axioms that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:19.710
we'll phrase in mathematical language to&nbsp;
make them sound relatively legitimate. Most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:25.830
modern mathematicians do not understand&nbsp;
these axioms. In fact, they hardly ever&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:30.330
use them. There's only a small cohort of&nbsp;
mathematicians that do. But nevertheless,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.330 --> 00:06:36.960
everybody pays lip service to them and&nbsp;
acknowledges that no doubt they are correct. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:43.230
one of my purposes to take the air out of this&nbsp;
inflated theory and to bring it down to earth.

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:49.470
Right now, however, is not quite the time to do&nbsp;
it because this entire development requires a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:55.620
little bit more sophistication and more careful&nbsp;
analysis. What I do want to show you, however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.620 --> 00:07:01.950
is that even if we restrict ourselves to the&nbsp;
natural numbers, an ordinary person can appreciate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:07.830
that it doesn't make sense to talk about this as&nbsp;
a completed whole. And the way we're going to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:14.130
that is by looking at bigger and bigger numbers.&nbsp;
Once we do that, then we get an appreciation for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:21.660
just the immensity of this infinite sequence.&nbsp;
So next time, we're going to look at the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:30.120
numbers and extremely big numbers. I hope you'll&nbsp;
join me for that. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks.

